Question 1

The data comes from Ultimate Tennis Statistics, a website that stores updated info on every player currently playing on the professional tour and the statistics of those who have played in the past. Many of their datasets include rankings, performance, tournaments, etc, but I chose the GOAT list because I can visualize all of these categories in one dataset that define players holistically. I chose tennis statistics because I started playing tennis when I was three years old, played throughout middle school, and played for varsity throughout high school. Tennis is my ultimate passion and when I grow up I aspire to become a data scientist or analyst for the professional tennis tour, and I feel this was my first chance to try extracting statistics on my favorite players.

Question 5

First Bivariate Analyses

## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

## [1] 0.9472883

For this scatterplot displaying the relationship between the number of grand slams and total rank points, there is a strong, linear positive correlation between the two variables because of a correlation coefficient of 0.95. cor(tennis_goat_data$number_grand_slams, tennis_goat_data$rank_points) was the code I used to generate this number. As seen, players with more grand slams tend to have higher rank points.

Second Bivariate Analyses

## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

## [1] 0.6151069

This scatterplot displays the relationship between the weeks at number one and according win percentage of the players, and there is a moderately, positive linear relationship between the variables because of a correlation coefficient of 0.615. The functioncor(tennis_goat_data$weeks_at_number_one, tennis_goat_data$win_percentage) was utilized to generate this number, and this shows that players who were the longest at the number one rank usually have higher win percentages.

This barplot displays the top 10 players of all the players by their Elo rating, which is essentially tracks a player rating that will increase more if they win against higher-rated opponents and less if they win against lower-rated opponents.

According to the graph, there is a positive correlation between players who have spent more weeks at number one and the amount of major events they have won like ATP 500s, Masters, and Futures tournaments. Also, players with higher win percentagges tend to cluster in the upper right area, indicating that a higher dominance at the number one spot usually means high win records and achievements.

Overall, I found that players with more grand slams had higher winniung percentages, and this makes sense since winning major tournaments correlates with strong, consistent performance. Also, there was a clear, positive relationship between weeks at number one and the number of major events won, showcasing that players who spend more time as the worlds top-ranked player tends to have more high value achievements. The trend amongst all the graphs show that the higher the independent variable, the more the dependent variable or the measure of success on the GOAT ranks.
